passages.text: F4Q25 Review: Robust Performance in F4Q But Conservative Guide to S& Up Catalysts in Relation to Execution and Update to FY26 Outlook

Nutanix delivered better revenue results as well as robust growth in ARR, delivering further evidence of the company's solid positioning to benefit from interest from Enterprise customers in leveraging its platforms, particularly in relation to a significant opportunity associated with VMware replacement. The robust performance in the quarter also enabled significant operating leverage to support robust EPS beat through a combination of better revenue and operating margins. That said, despite the robust results, the bigger focus for investors will largely be in relation to the FY26 guide which is for \(15\%\) revenue growth following \(18\%\) growth in FY25, likely leading to concerns in relation to the company cycling past the early innings of the tailwinds in relation to the VMware opportunity leading to a moderation in the growth rate from FY25 to FY26. However, the underlying drivers of the deceleration in the revenue growth implied in the FY26 guide of \(15\%\) growth vs. \(18\%\) in FY25 appears to be a combination of various conservative assumptions from the company, including 1) assumption of shorter contract duration in FY26 relative to FY25, following expansion in FY25; 2) assumption of moderation in renewal pace on account of a larger renewal base as well as new customers more recently starting at a deal size higher than typical, leading the company to be cautious around similar pace of renewal increases as evidenced historically; and 3) continued mixed macro backdrop, including constrained spending from the Public Sector. The above drivers, while representing prudent assumptions from the company, do leave room for upside as the company delivers robust performance similar to F4Q25 and potentially raises the full- year FY26 outlook with higher visibility into the year. In relation to the VMware replacement opportunity, Nutanix continues to leverage the multi- year opportunity, with momentum of Enterprise customers migrating to Nutanix helping drive an acceleration of new customer/ logo wins which tracked to an increase of over 2,700 customers on a y/y basis, relative to more than 2,600 customers in F3Q and 2,500 customers in F2Q and more than 2,200 in F1Q. We see the combination of acceleration in new customer wins as well as increasing contribution from platforms launched in partnership with Dell (in relation to which Nutanix booked two new customers much earlier than anticipated and to be launched in partnership with Pure Storage) to support robust momentum of revenue and ARR growth in FY26 and beyond, delivering potential upsides relative to the conservative guidance issued by the company. While our earnings forecasts for the company remain largely unchanged, we are lowering our Dec- 26 price target for the company to \(81 from \$90 prior with near- term sentiment on the shares likely to remain muted until further execution- led upsides moderate investor concern relative to deceleration of revenue growth.

Nutanix, the pioneer of the Hyperconverged Infrastructure (HCI) market, offers an enterprise cloud platform that leverages web-scale engineering to natively converge compute, storage,networking, and virtualization into a highly scalable, resilient,software-defined solution based on commodity hardware components. We believe Nutanix's compelling value proposition is completely reinventing the IT infrastructure playbook. While the competitive landscape for Hyperconverged Infrastructure continues to evolve quickly as the legacy IT infrastructure competitors recognize the threat that HCI poses and are quickly pivoting toward it, we believe Nutanix leads the pack in terms of market share as well as mind share, driving our Overweight rating for the shares.

We are lowering our December 2026 price target to $81 (vs. $90 prior) based on valuing our CY27E EPS at 30x target P/E multiple, which is lower than the current trading multiple, but still implying a modestly higher EV/uFCF relative to infrastructure software peers given higher margins and FCF conversion.

Meanwhile, gross margins tracked to \(88.3\%\) (vs. JPMc of \(86.8\%\) and consensus of \(87.8\%\) ), which was offset to some extent by seasonally high opex ( \(70\%\) of sales \(85.66\%\) on average for first three quarters), still resulting in operating margins of \(18.3\%\) , relative to JPMc/consensus of \(16.3\%\) and guide of \(16.0\%\) , and translated to EPS of \(\) 0.37\(vs. JPMc of\) \ \(0.31\) and consensus of \(\) 0.33\$ .

- F1Q26 (Oct-end) Guidance: Revenues and operating profits guided to track largely in-line with consensus. Nutanix is guiding revenues to \(\) 670-\(\) 680\(mn (midpoint of\) \ \(675\) mn) vs. JPMc of \(\) 675\(mn and consensus of\) \ \(677\) mn. Operating margins are guided to \(19.5 - 20.5\%\) vs. JPMc of \(19.6\%\) and consensus of \(19.8\%\) , resulting in an implied operating profit of \(\) 135\(mn (vs. JPMc of\) \ \(132\) mn and consensus of \(\) 134\(mn), which in our view implies EPS guide of\) \ \(0.41\) vs. JPMc of \(\) 0.40\(and consensus of\) \ \(0.42\) .

- FY26 (Jul-end) Guidance: Revenues and operating profits to track largely in-line with consensus. Nutanix is guiding FY26 revenue of \(\) 2.90\(bn -\) \ \(2.94\) bn, vs. JPMc/consensus of \(\) 2.93\(bn/\) \ \(2.92\) bn heading into the print, while operating margins are guided to be \(21 - 22\%\) (vs. JPMc of \(21.8\%\) and consensus of \(21.3\%\) ), resulting in an implied operating profit of \(\) 628\(mn (vs. JPMc of\) \ \(639\) mn and consensus of \(\) 621\(mn).
Nutanix (Overweight; Price Target: \(81.00\) )
